,17.96,19.19,23.22,30.15,23.87,21.16,33.4,29.43,26.09,28.71,23.88,19.74,26.21,27.16,32.45,25.88,23.12,22.83,21.67,19.81,20.53,18.49,22.61,17.07,20.09,19.14,13.88,14.18,13.86,16.46,13.82,16.9,19.32,14.91,12.8,12.48,13.08,13.26,14.24,14.44,13.01,18.0,12.69,14.28,12.48,12.51,17.69,14.65,19.45,16.96,18.03,15.2,13.9,27.62,19.54,15.84,15.66,24.23,21.51,28.45,18.62,17.69,17.48,17.2,17.52,14.22,14.76,16.63,17.3,17.51,16.08,14.0,15.84,18.64,17.93,22.37,21.04,17.83,18.06,18.92,17.65,18.77]}},"releases":{"fomc":"Jul 29","ecb":"Jul 23","jobs":"Aug 7","ismMfg":"Aug 3","ismServices":"Aug 5","claims":"Weekly (Thu)","cpi":"Aug 12 (est.)","ppi":"Aug 13 (est.)","retail":"Aug 17 (est.)","housing":"Aug 17 (est.)","existing":"Jul 21 (est.)","pce":"Jul 28 (est.)","gdp":"Jul 28 (est.)","umich":"Aug 14 (est.)","chinaPMI":"Jul 31 (est.)","daily":"Daily","gdpnowKey":"Updates ~weekly"},"commentary":{"source":"claude","generated":"2026-07-20","items":[{"tag":"Energy","text":"WTI ($79.20) and Brent ($81.62) have rebounded sharply from post-Hormuz-reopening lows \u2014 Brent is up ~$5.93 w/w \u2014 as renewed exchanges of fire in the Gulf (Trump declared the Iran ceasefire over on July 8) revived supply disruption fears. The IEA estimates global supply remains ~9.4 mb/d below pre-war levels, with the market balance contingent on sustained Strait transit recovery. For credit investors, energy-sector issuers and commodity-exposed leveraged borrowers face a highly volatile input cost environment, while E&P credits benefit from elevated realized prices."},{"tag":"Inflation","text":"Headline CPI has fallen to 3.46% (from 4.17% prior) and core CPI to 2.57%, signaling meaningful sequential disinflation \u2014 but PCE remains stickier at 4.07% headline and 3.41% core, well above target. PPI at 5.51% and ISM Services Prices at 67.7 (a 4-month low but still deeply elevated) signal upstream pressure persisting into margins. For credit, bifurcated inflation \u2014 cooling goods, sticky services and energy \u2014 complicates the refinancing calculus for issuers hoping rate cuts will bail out 2026-27 maturities."},{"tag":"Policy/Rates","text":"The Fed holds at 3.75% while the 10-year UST has climbed to 4.57% (up 17bps w/w) and the 2s10s curve steepens to +37bps \u2014 a bear-steepening that reflects both inflation persistence and fiscal premium rather than growth optimism. The ECB unexpectedly hiked 25bps in June to 2.25% on energy-driven inflation, with its July 23 meeting likely to assess whether further tightening is needed. For special situations credit, the rate-higher-for-longer path is the dominant regime: distressed refinancings at par-equivalent remain challenged, and any spread compression thesis depends heavily on inflation trajectory."},{"tag":"Credit Markets","text":"HY OAS ticked wider to 273bps (from 267bps) and IG OAS to 79bps (from 76bps) \u2014 modest moves but directionally risk-off, consistent with the geopolitical escalation mid-week and the 10-year yield backup. VIX at 18.77 (up from 17.65) remains contained relative to the macro uncertainty, suggesting credit vol may be underpricing tail risks around renewed Hormuz disruption or a tariff shock. Special situations desks should watch for idiosyncratic stress in energy-import-heavy issuers and sectors with high tariff exposure as spread widening accelerates selectively."},{"tag":"Labor","text":"Payrolls collapsed to 57K in June (from 129K prior), a significant deceleration that points to a softening labor market even as unemployment ticked down to 4.2% and claims fell to 208K. Average hourly earnings accelerated to 3.52% y/y, a potential wage-price stickiness signal that complicates the Fed's dovish case. For credit, a slowing labor market with still-elevated wages is a late-cycle warning sign: consumer-facing leveraged issuers face rising default risk if real disposable income erodes, particularly among lower-income cohorts already relying on revolving credit."},{"tag":"Growth/Consumer","text":"GDPNow has recovered to 1.68% annualized but the growth picture is uneven: retail sales rose only +0.2% m/m in June (vs. +1.0% in May), with the headline dragged by a 5.3% drop in gas station receipts; the control group rose a healthier +0.5%. UMich consumer sentiment collapsed to 44.8, near historic lows, while the saving rate holds at 3.0% \u2014 a thin buffer. ISM Services at 54.0 keeps the expansion intact for a 24th consecutive month, but for credit investors, the divergence between backward-looking hard data and cratering soft data is a key watch item for H2 2026 fundamental credit deterioration."},{"tag":"Housing","text":"The 30-year mortgage rate rose to 6.55% (from 6.43%), adding further pressure to an already strained market \u2014 existing home sales fell to 4.09M SAAR from 4.19M prior, while housing starts surged to 1,427K (from 1,199K), likely reflecting a release of builder backlog rather than a demand-driven impulse. For credit investors, CMBS and homebuilder paper face divergent signals: starts strength may support homebuilder revenues near-term, but affordability constraints and rising rates cap upside and increase refinancing risk on floating-rate mortgages and construction loans."}]},"extraSeries":{"ecb":{"value":"2.25%","delta":"Raised +25bps at June 11 meeting (effective June 17), first hike since 2023, driven by energy/inflation shock; July 23 meeting to reassess further tightening","dir":"up"},"chinaPMI":{"value":"50.3","delta":"NBS official mfg PMI; up from 50.0 in May, beat 50.1 forecast; AI/tech export demand driving expansion while domestic demand and real estate remain weak","dir":"up"},"ismServices":{"value":"54.0","delta":"Down 0.5pts from 54.5 in May, 24th consecutive month of expansion; employment returned to expansion (51.2); prices eased to 4-month low of 67.7","dir":"down"},"retailSales":{"value":"+0.2% m/m","delta":"Decelerated sharply from May's +1.0%; gas station receipts -5.3% dragged headline; control group +0.5%, nonstore retail +1.9% (Prime Day boost)","dir":"down"},"existingHome":{"value":"4.09M","delta":"Down from 4.19M prior month (SAAR); 30yr mortgage at 6.55% constraining affordability and transaction volumes","dir":"down"}},"themes":{"refiWall":"The 2026-27 HY and leveraged loan refinancing wall remains acutely stressed: the 10-year UST at 4.57% combined with HY OAS at 273bps implies all-in yields above 7.3%, making opportunistic refinancing of vintage 2021-22 low-coupon paper deeply dilutive; the payrolls miss and sticky PCE inflation reduce the probability of Fed rate cuts that would have provided relief, and a growing cohort of CCC-rated issuers face extension risk turning into default risk as maturity cliffs approach in late 2026 and 2027.","tariffs":"US tariff policy remains a live, compounding risk: Trump is reportedly pushing for a 15-20% minimum tariff floor on all EU goods, Section 301 probes targeting overcapacity and forced labor continue, and a 10% Section 122 levy on China was set to expire in July \u2014 creating front-loaded import demand that may now reverse; ISM Manufacturing survey respondents cited tariffs in 18% of June comments alongside the Iran war, and the dual shock of energy costs and trade friction is showing up directly in elevated input prices and supply chain uncertainty for leveraged issuers.","mideast":"The US-Iran conflict and Strait of Hormuz disruption \u2014 which the IEA characterized as the largest oil supply disruption in market history \u2014 is in a fragile partial-recovery phase: global supply rebounded 4.1 mb/d in June as Strait flows partially resumed, but renewed hostilities as of July 8 (Trump declaring the ceasefire over) sent Brent up 5%+ intraday, and the EIA still projects global inventory draws of 2.2 mb/d through Q3 before a potential surplus in Q4; credit investors should monitor energy-price volatility as the primary transmission channel into inflation, central bank policy, and ultimately corporate credit quality and default rates."}}